{"title_page": "Melita (personification)", "text_new": "[[File:Malta 1922 One Pound.jpg|thumb|right|Melita depicted on a \u00a31 stamp designed by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] issued on 28 August 1922]]\n\n'''Melita''' is a [[national personification]] of [[Malta]]. The name originated from the [[Phoenicia|Punic]]-[[Roman Empire|Roman]] town of [[Melite (ancient city)|Melite]] (\u039c\u03b5\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03b7, ''Melite'' in [[Ancient Greek]]), the ancient capital of Malta which eventually developed into the city of [[Mdina]].\n\nThe symbolic depiction of a country as a woman called by the Latin name of that country was common in the 19th century (such as [[Britannia]], [[Germania (personification)|Germania]], [[Hibernia (personification)|Hibernia]] and [[Helvetia]]).\n\n==Description and origins==\n[[File:Auberge de Provence Ceiling Valletta.JPG|thumb|left|Ceiling fresco at [[Auberge de Provence]] by [[Nicolau Nasoni]], depicting a personification of \"Religion\" which bears similarities with later depictions of Melita]]\n\nThe earliest known personification of Malta dates back to 1481. This depicts a woman holding a [[sceptre]] in one hand and the emblem of Malta in the other, and it was produced for the choir of the [[St Paul's Cathedral, Mdina|Mdina cathedral]].<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\"/>\n\nThe personification of Melita is often depicted as a female wearing military attire, prominently displaying the [[Maltese cross]]. This is said to represent Malta's strategic importance in a military and maritime context, while also reflecting the islands' Catholic traditions. This iconography is inspired by that of the Roman goddess [[Minerva]] and the allegory of fortitude in a [[Christianity|Christian]] context.<ref name=\"g\u0127onnella\"/> It also bears similarities to depictions of [[Britannia]].<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\">{{cite journal |last1=Kinnane-Roelofsma |first1=Derk |title=Britannia and Melita: Pseudomorphic Sisters |journal=Journal of the Warbourg and Courtauld Insitute |date=1996 |volume=59 |pages=130\u2013147}}</ref>\n\nThis depiction is said to have originally represented the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]], which [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|ruled Malta]] between the 16th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\"/> An example of an allegorical painting which bears similarities to later depictions of Melita is an 18th century fresco at [[Auberge de Provence]] by [[Nicolau Nasoni]]. The painting depicts a female figure wearing armour with a Maltese cross and holding a sword and shield, and it is said to represent the \"Religion\", a common nickname for the Order.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sultana |first1=Sharon |title=The National Museum of Archaeology \u2013 The Neolithic Period |date=2006 |publisher=Heritage Books |location=[[Malta]] |isbn=99932-7-076-8 |page=5}}</ref> After the [[French invasion of Malta|Order's expulsion from Malta]] in 1798, the personification came to represent Malta itself due to the strong links between the islands' identity and the Order.<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\"/><ref name=\"g\u0127onnella\"/>\n\nIn the first half of the 20th century, a woman wearing an ''[[g\u0127onnella]]'' was sometimes used as an alternative personification of Malta distinct from Melita.<ref name=\"g\u0127onnella\">{{cite journal |last1=Debono |first1=Sandro |title=G\u0127onnella: A British-styled allegory for twentieth-century Malta |journal=Peasant Costumes - Insights into Rural Life and Society |date=2012 |pages=67\u201375 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/30918/1/GHonnella_-_A_British-Styled_Allegory_fo.pdf |publisher=Heritage Malta |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411120619/https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/30918/1/GHonnella_-_A_British-Styled_Allegory_fo.pdf |archivedate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Depiction on stamps and currency==\n[[File:1902 2s6d Olive-Green revenue stamp of Malta.jpg|thumb|The 1899 Melita stamp design, overprinted as a [[revenue stamp]] in 1902]]\n\n===Stamps===\n{{further|Melita issue}}\n\nMelita has been portrayed a number of times on Maltese [[Postage stamps and postal history of Malta|postage]] or [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue stamps]]. The allegorical figure first appeared on a 2[[shilling|s]]/6d olive-grey stamp in 1899, where she was depicted holding a sword and a shield, the latter emblazoned with the [[Maltese cross]]. In the background were the flags of Malta and of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The \"Melita\" Stamp of Malta |url=https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |website=Mintage World |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122142635/https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |archivedate=22 January 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> The designer of this stamp is not known,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Joseph |title=[[JB Catalogue|The J.B. Catalogue of Malta Stamps and Postal History]] |date=2014 |publisher=Sliema Stamp Shop Publishers |location=[[Sliema]] |page=6 |edition=22}}</ref> and it remained in use until the early 1920s, being reissued with a different [[watermark]] in 1919.<ref name=\"sg\">{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Stamp Catalogue: Commonwealth and British Empire Stamps 1840\u20131970 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Stanley Gibbons]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-85259-918-1 |pages=401\u2013402 |edition=117}}</ref> Special printings of the 1899 design, sometimes in new colours or watermarks, were also issued with [[overprint]]s for [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue purposes]] between 1902 and 1908.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Andrew|title=Malta|url=http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|website=Revenue Reverend|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924105952/http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|archivedate=24 September 2017|date=2011\u201317}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1922 and 1926, a series of dual-purpose postage and revenue stamps known as the [[Melita issue]] was issued to commemorate Malta's self-government. The stamps had two designs: one by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and the other by [[Gianni Vella]]. Caruana Dingli's design, which was used for the pence and pound values, depicts Melita as a robed and helmeted figure holding a [[rudder]], representing Malta as being in control of her own destiny, while Vella's design shows Melita embracing Britannia, representing the link between Britain and Malta as sisters or mother and daughter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Melita Issue of Malta Stamps: 1922\u201326|url=http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|website=British Empire Philately|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113650/http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Malta's 1922 Melita issue: Fine art or poorly done stamps? |url=https://www.linns.com/news/us-stamps-postal-history/2017/january/malta-melita-stamp-issue-fine-art-poorly-done.html |website=[[Linn's Stamp News]] |date=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75cWftBrr|archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Currency===\n{{further|Melita bullion coins}}\n\nA depiction of Melita based on Caruana Dingli's design appeared on the fifth series of [[Maltese lira]] banknotes which were in use from 1989 until Malta adopted the [[euro]] in 2008. The watermark on these and previous banknotes also shows the head of the allegorical figure Melita.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maltese banknotes \u2013 5th Series and enhanced version (not legal tender after 31 January 2008)|url=http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|publisher=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227162525/http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|archivedate=27 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline Banknotes |url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |website=[[Central Bank of Malta]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122163451/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref> The allegorical figure also appears on the [[Melita bullion coins]] minted since 2018.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\">{{cite web|title=Melita bullion coins 2018|url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|website=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121120928/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Personifications of Malta}}\n\n{{National personifications}}\n\n[[Category:National personifications]]\n[[Category:History of Malta]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Malta]]\n[[Category:Fictional Maltese people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Malta 1922 One Pound.jpg|thumb|right|Melita depicted on a \u00a31 stamp designed by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] issued on 28 August 1922]]\n\n'''Melita''' is a [[national personification]] of [[Malta]]. The name originated from the [[Phoenicia|Punic]]-[[Roman Empire|Roman]] town of [[Melite (ancient city)|Melite]] (\u039c\u03b5\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03b7, ''Melite'' in [[Ancient Greek]]), the ancient capital of Malta which eventually developed into the city of [[Mdina]].\n\nThe symbolic depiction of a country as a woman called by the Latin name of that country was common in the 19th century (such as [[Britannia]], [[Germania (personification)|Germania]], [[Hibernia (personification)|Hibernia]] and [[Helvetia]]).\n\n==Description and origins==\n[[File:Auberge de Provence Ceiling Valletta.JPG|thumb|left|Ceiling fresco at [[Auberge de Provence]] by [[Nicolau Nasoni]], depicting a personification of \"Religion\" which bears similarities with later depictions of Melita]]\n\nThe earliest known personification of Malta dates back to 1481. This depicts a woman holding a [[sceptre]] in one hand and the emblem of Malta in the other, and it was produced for the choir of the [[St Paul's Cathedral, Mdina|Mdina cathedral]].<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\"/>\n\nThe personification of Melita is often depicted as a female wearing military attire, prominently displaying the [[Maltese cross]]. This is said to represent Malta's strategic importance in a military and maritime context, while also reflecting the islands' Catholic traditions. This iconography is inspired by that of the Roman goddess [[Minerva]] and the allegory of fortitude in a [[Christian]] context.<ref name=\"g\u0127onnella\"/> It also bears similarities to depictions of [[Britannia]].<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\">{{cite journal |last1=Kinnane-Roelofsma |first1=Derk |title=Britannia and Melita: Pseudomorphic Sisters |journal=Journal of the Warbourg and Courtauld Insitute |date=1996 |volume=59 |pages=130\u2013147}}</ref>\n\nThis depiction is said to have originally represented the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]], which [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|ruled Malta]] between the 16th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\"/> An example of an allegorical painting which bears similarities to later depictions of Melita is an 18th century fresco at [[Auberge de Provence]] by [[Nicolau Nasoni]]. The painting depicts a female figure wearing armour with a Maltese cross and holding a sword and shield, and it is said to represent the \"Religion\", a common nickname for the Order.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sultana |first1=Sharon |title=The National Museum of Archaeology \u2013 The Neolithic Period |date=2006 |publisher=Heritage Books |location=[[Malta]] |isbn=99932-7-076-8 |page=5}}</ref> After the [[French invasion of Malta|Order's expulsion from Malta]] in 1798, the personification came to represent Malta itself due to the strong links between the islands' identity and the Order.<ref name=\"kinnane-roelofsma\"/><ref name=\"g\u0127onnella\"/>\n\nIn the first half of the 20th century, a woman wearing an ''[[g\u0127onnella]]'' was sometimes used as an alternative personification of Malta distinct from Melita.<ref name=\"g\u0127onnella\">{{cite journal |last1=Debono |first1=Sandro |title=G\u0127onnella: A British-styled allegory for twentieth-century Malta |journal=Peasant Costumes - Insights into Rural Life and Society |date=2012 |pages=67\u201375 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/30918/1/GHonnella_-_A_British-Styled_Allegory_fo.pdf |publisher=Heritage Malta |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411120619/https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/30918/1/GHonnella_-_A_British-Styled_Allegory_fo.pdf |archivedate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Depiction on stamps and currency==\n[[File:1902 2s6d Olive-Green revenue stamp of Malta.jpg|thumb|The 1899 Melita stamp design, overprinted as a [[revenue stamp]] in 1902]]\n\n===Stamps===\n{{further|Melita issue}}\n\nMelita has been portrayed a number of times on Maltese [[Postage stamps and postal history of Malta|postage]] or [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue stamps]]. The allegorical figure first appeared on a 2[[shilling|s]]/6d olive-grey stamp in 1899, where she was depicted holding a sword and a shield, the latter emblazoned with the [[Maltese cross]]. In the background were the flags of Malta and of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The \"Melita\" Stamp of Malta |url=https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |website=Mintage World |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122142635/https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |archivedate=22 January 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> The designer of this stamp is not known,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Joseph |title=[[JB Catalogue|The J.B. Catalogue of Malta Stamps and Postal History]] |date=2014 |publisher=Sliema Stamp Shop Publishers |location=[[Sliema]] |page=6 |edition=22}}</ref> and it remained in use until the early 1920s, being reissued with a different [[watermark]] in 1919.<ref name=\"sg\">{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Stamp Catalogue: Commonwealth and British Empire Stamps 1840\u20131970 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Stanley Gibbons]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-85259-918-1 |pages=401\u2013402 |edition=117}}</ref> Special printings of the 1899 design, sometimes in new colours or watermarks, were also issued with [[overprint]]s for [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue purposes]] between 1902 and 1908.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Andrew|title=Malta|url=http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|website=Revenue Reverend|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924105952/http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|archivedate=24 September 2017|date=2011\u201317}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1922 and 1926, a series of dual-purpose postage and revenue stamps known as the [[Melita issue]] was issued to commemorate Malta's self-government. The stamps had two designs: one by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and the other by [[Gianni Vella]]. Caruana Dingli's design, which was used for the pence and pound values, depicts Melita as a robed and helmeted figure holding a [[rudder]], representing Malta as being in control of her own destiny, while Vella's design shows Melita embracing Britannia, representing the link between Britain and Malta as sisters or mother and daughter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Melita Issue of Malta Stamps: 1922\u201326|url=http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|website=British Empire Philately|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113650/http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Malta's 1922 Melita issue: Fine art or poorly done stamps? |url=https://www.linns.com/news/us-stamps-postal-history/2017/january/malta-melita-stamp-issue-fine-art-poorly-done.html |website=[[Linn's Stamp News]] |date=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75cWftBrr|archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Currency===\n{{further|Melita bullion coins}}\n\nA depiction of Melita based on Caruana Dingli's design appeared on the fifth series of [[Maltese lira]] banknotes which were in use from 1989 until Malta adopted the [[euro]] in 2008. The watermark on these and previous banknotes also shows the head of the allegorical figure Melita.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maltese banknotes \u2013 5th Series and enhanced version (not legal tender after 31 January 2008)|url=http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|publisher=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227162525/http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|archivedate=27 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline Banknotes |url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |website=[[Central Bank of Malta]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122163451/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref> The allegorical figure also appears on the [[Melita bullion coins]] minted since 2018.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\">{{cite web|title=Melita bullion coins 2018|url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|website=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121120928/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Personifications of Malta}}\n\n{{National personifications}}\n\n[[Category:National personifications]]\n[[Category:History of Malta]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Malta]]\n[[Category:Fictional Maltese people]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toChristian(link changed toChristianity) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melita_(personification)"}
{"title_page": "Scratch Orchestra", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}\nThe '''Scratch Orchestra''' was an experimental [[musical ensemble]] founded in the spring of 1969 by [[Cornelius Cardew]], [[Michael Parsons (composer)|Michael Parsons]] and [[Howard Skempton]].<ref name=\"PHD\">[http://www.stefan-szczelkun.org.uk/phd102.htm Stefan Szczelkun Ph.D. thesis]{{Full|date=April 2017}}<!--Needs title, year, school, etc.--></ref> \n\nIn the draft constitution published in the ''Musical Times'' of June 1969, Cardew defines a scratch orchestra as: \"a large number of enthusiasts pooling their resources (not primarily material resources) and assembling for action (music-making, performance, edification)\".<ref>Cornelius Cardew, \"[title]\", ''The Musical Times'' [vol.], [issue no.] (June 1969): {{Page needed|date=May 2017}}.</ref>  The Orchestra reflected Cardew's musical philosophy at that time. This meant that anyone could join, [[graphic notation (music)|graphic scores]] were used (rather than traditional [[sheet music]]), and there was an emphasis on improvisation. The Scratch Orchestra arose from Cardew's 'Experimental Music' class at [[Morley College]], London, which served as a venue for extra rehearsals for Scratch Orchestra concerts, but Scratch Orchestra rehearsals were also held separately. [[New Zealand]] artist/musician [[Philip Dadson]] was amongst those at [[Morley College]] who were in the foundation group for the Scratch Orchestra and, after returning to [[New Zealand]], established a NZ Scratch Orchestra in 1970, which evolved into the group [[From Scratch (music group)|From Scratch]] in 1974.\n\nThe first meeting of the Scratch Orchestra was at [[St Katharine Docks]], 1 July 1969.  It was announced by means of a \"Draft Constitution\", published in ''The Musical Times'' in June 1969.  The Draft Constitution set out categories of musical activity: Improvisation Rites, Popular Classics, Compositions, and Research Projects.  Cardew also proposed that the responsibility of programming of concerts be assigned in reverse seniority, so that the first concert, on 1 November 1969 at Hampstead Town Hall, was designed by [[Christopher Hobbs]], an eighteen-year-old student of Cardew's at the Royal Academy of Music. Original members included [[Carole Finer]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nDespite the emphasis on free improvisation, the varying experience of the members, and the \"do your own thing\" free aesthetic of the time, the Scratch Orchestra was a disciplined ensemble. Eventually the strains of Cardew's \"reverse seniority\", tensions between musically-trained and non-musically-trained members, and an increasing interest in political [[aesthetics]] led to a gradual change in the activities, and then the outlook of the ensemble. It was effectively inoperative by 1974.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Edwin Pr\u00e9vost, ed.; introduction by Michael Parsons, ''Cornelius Cardew: A Reader'' (Harlow, Essex: Copula, 2006). {{ISBN|0-9525492-2-0}}. (A collection of Cornelius Cardew's published writings together with commentaries and responses from Richard Barrett, Christopher Fox, Brian Dennis, Anton Lukoszevieze, Michael Nyman, Eddie Pr\u00e9vost, David Ryan, Howard Skempton, Dave Smith, John Tilbury and Christian Wolff.)\n* Cornelius Cardew, ed. ''Scratch Music'' (Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press). {{ISBN|0-262-53025-2}}. (Scratch Orchestra draft constitution, notes, scores, catalogue, and 1001 Activities.)\n* Cornelius Cardew, ''\"Stockhausen Serves Imperialism\", and Other Articles: with Commentary and Notes'' (London: Latimer New Dimensions, 1974) ([http://www.ubu.com/historical/cardew/cardew_stockhausen.pdf download PDF])\n* Michael Parsons, ed. ''25 Years from Scratch: The Scratch Orchestra'' (London: London Musicians\u2019 Collective, 1994) ([http://www.adashboard.org/25years_scratch.pdf download PDF])\n* Stefan Szczelkun ed. ''Improvisation Rites: from John Cage's 'Song Books' to the Scratch Orchestra's 'Nature Study Notes'. Collective practices 2011 \u2013 2017'' (Routine Art Co. 2017) \n* John Tilbury, ''Cornelius Cardew (1936\u20131981): A Life Unfinished'' (Essex: Copula, 2008)\n* Katie Macfarlane, Rob Stone, Grant Watson, eds., ''Play for Today: Cornelius Cardew'' (London: Drawing Room; Antwerp: Museum van Hedendaagse Kunst Antwerpen (M HKA), 2009) {{ISBN|0955829917}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://soundcloud.com/szczels/nature-study-notes-16mins Nature Study Notes] [[Carole Finer]] and [[Stefan Szczelkun]] read and discuss the verbal scores that kicked off the Scratch Orchestra in 1969.\n* [http://www.intuitivemusic.dk/iima/so.htm Nature Study Notes] texts at [http://www.intuitivemusic.dk/iima/ International Improvised Music Archive].\n* [https://maydayrooms.org/archives/the-scratch-orchestra/ The Scratch Orchestra]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Free improvisation ensembles]]\n[[Category:British experimental musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1969]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}\nThe '''Scratch Orchestra''' was an experimental [[musical ensemble]] founded in the spring of 1969 by [[Cornelius Cardew]], [[Michael Parsons (composer)|Michael Parsons]] and [[Howard Skempton]].<ref name=\"PHD\">[http://www.stefan-szczelkun.org.uk/phd102.htm Stefan Szczelkun Ph.D. thesis]{{Full|date=April 2017}}<!--Needs title, year, school, etc.--></ref> \n\nIn the draft constitution published in the ''Musical Times'' of June 1969, Cardew defines a scratch orchestra as: \"a large number of enthusiasts pooling their resources (not primarily material resources) and assembling for action (music-making, performance, edification)\".<ref>Cornelius Cardew, \"[title]\", ''The Musical Times'' [vol.], [issue no.] (June 1969): {{Page needed|date=May 2017}}.</ref>  The Orchestra reflected Cardew's musical philosophy at that time. This meant that anyone could join, [[graphic notation (music)|graphic scores]] were used (rather than traditional [[sheet music]]), and there was an emphasis on improvisation. The Scratch Orchestra arose from Cardew's 'Experimental Music' class at [[Morley College]], London, which served as a venue for extra rehearsals for Scratch Orchestra concerts, but Scratch Orchestra rehearsals were also held separately. [[New Zealand]] artist/musician [[Philip Dadson]] was amongst those at [[Morley College]] who were in the foundation group for the Scratch Orchestra and, after returning to [[New Zealand]], established a NZ Scratch Orchestra in 1970, which evolved into the group [[From Scratch (music group)|From Scratch]] in 1974.\n\nThe first meeting of the Scratch Orchestra was at [[St Katharine Docks]] , 1 July 1969.  It was announced by means of a \"Draft Constitution\", published in ''The Musical Times'' in June 1969.  The Draft Constitution set out categories of musical activity: Improvisation Rites, Popular Classics, Compositions, and Research Projects.  Cardew also proposed that the responsibility of programming of concerts be assigned in reverse seniority, so that the first concert, on 1 November 1969 at Hampstead Town Hall, was designed by [[Christopher Hobbs]], an eighteen-year-old student of Cardew's at the Royal Academy of Music. Original members included [[Carole Finer]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nDespite the emphasis on free improvisation, the varying experience of the members, and the \"do your own thing\" free aesthetic of the time, the Scratch Orchestra was a disciplined ensemble. Eventually the strains of Cardew's \"reverse seniority\", tensions between musically-trained and non-musically-trained members, and an increasing interest in political [[aesthetics]] led to a gradual change in the activities, and then the outlook of the ensemble. It was effectively inoperative by 1974.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Edwin Pr\u00e9vost, ed.; introduction by Michael Parsons, ''Cornelius Cardew: A Reader'' (Harlow, Essex: Copula, 2006). {{ISBN|0-9525492-2-0}}. (A collection of Cornelius Cardew's published writings together with commentaries and responses from Richard Barrett, Christopher Fox, Brian Dennis, Anton Lukoszevieze, Michael Nyman, Eddie Pr\u00e9vost, David Ryan, Howard Skempton, Dave Smith, John Tilbury and Christian Wolff.)\n* Cornelius Cardew, ed. ''Scratch Music'' (Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press). {{ISBN|0-262-53025-2}}. (Scratch Orchestra draft constitution, notes, scores, catalogue, and 1001 Activities.)\n* Cornelius Cardew, ''\"Stockhausen Serves Imperialism\", and Other Articles: with Commentary and Notes'' (London: Latimer New Dimensions, 1974) ([http://www.ubu.com/historical/cardew/cardew_stockhausen.pdf download PDF])\n* Michael Parsons, ed. ''25 Years from Scratch: The Scratch Orchestra'' (London: London Musicians\u2019 Collective, 1994) ([http://www.adashboard.org/25years_scratch.pdf download PDF])\n* Stefan Szczelkun ed. ''Improvisation Rites: from John Cage's 'Song Books' to the Scratch Orchestra's 'Nature Study Notes'. Collective practices 2011 \u2013 2017'' (Routine Art Co. 2017) \n* John Tilbury, ''Cornelius Cardew (1936\u20131981): A Life Unfinished'' (Essex: Copula, 2008)\n* Katie Macfarlane, Rob Stone, Grant Watson, eds., ''Play for Today: Cornelius Cardew'' (London: Drawing Room; Antwerp: Museum van Hedendaagse Kunst Antwerpen (M HKA), 2009) {{ISBN|0955829917}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://soundcloud.com/szczels/nature-study-notes-16mins Nature Study Notes] [[Carole Finer]] and [[Stefan Szczelkun]] read and discuss the verbal scores that kicked off the Scratch Orchestra in 1969.\n* [http://www.intuitivemusic.dk/iima/so.htm Nature Study Notes] texts at [http://www.intuitivemusic.dk/iima/ International Improvised Music Archive].\n* [https://maydayrooms.org/archives/the-scratch-orchestra/ The Scratch Orchestra]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Free improvisation en