{"title_page": "Anita Raj (academic)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=July 2018}}\n{{COI|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Anita Raj\n| image = \n| image_size = 251px\n| caption = Anita Raj\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|12|29}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = [[United States]]\n| citizenship = [[United States|American]]\n| fields = [[Child Marriage]] <br /> [[Intimate Partner Violence]] <br /> [[Reproductive Health]] <br /> [[Substance abuse]] <br /> [[Sexual Violence]] <br /> [[Sexual Assault]] <br /> [[Gender Equity]]\n| workplaces = [[University of California, San Diego]] <br /> Center on Gender Equity & Health\n| alma_mater = [[Mississippi College]] <br /> (1991) <br /> [[University of Georgia]] <br /> (1995, 1996)\n| known_for = [[Child Marriage]] in South Asia\n}}\n\n'''Anita Raj''' (born December 29, 1970) is an American [[developmental psychologist]] and global public health researcher focused on [[sexual and reproductive health]], maternal and child health, and gender inequalities including gender-based violence, discrimination and bias. She is a Tata Chancellor Professor of Society and Health and is a Professor in the Departments of Medicine and Education Studies at the [[University of California, San Diego]]. She is also the Founding Director of UCSD's Center on Gender Equity and Health.\n\n== Career ==\n=== Research ===\nRaj's research interests include development and evaluation of sexual, reproductive and maternal-child behavioral health interventions for socially vulnerable populations; assessment of gendered, social and cultural vulnerabilities for sexual and reproductive health concerns, [[intimate partner violence]], and [[child marriage]]; and measurement of structural and systems level [[gender inequalities]] in health. This work includes studies in South Asia, Sub-Saharan Africa, Russia and the United States.\n\nShe is a research scientist trained in developmental psychology. Her research includes epidemiological and qualitative assessment of gendered, social, and cultural vulnerabilities, specializing in reproductive,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Raj|first=Anita|last2=Ghule|first2=Mohan|last3=Ritter|first3=Julie|last4=Battala|first4=Madhusudana|last5=Gajanan|first5=Velhal|last6=Nair|first6=Saritha|last7=Dasgupta|first7=Anindita|last8=Silverman|first8=Jay G.|last9=Balaiah|first9=Donta|date=2016-05-11|title=Cluster Randomized Controlled Trial Evaluation of a Gender Equity and Family Planning Intervention for Married Men and Couples in Rural India|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=5|pages=e0153190|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0153190|pmid=27167981|pmc=4864357|issn=1932-6203}}</ref> maternal, neonatal, child, and adolescent health concerns across national settings; assessment of etiology and public health impact of gender inequities including early and child marriage,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Raj|first=Anita|last2=Saggurti|first2=Niranjan|last3=Balaiah|first3=Donta|last4=Silverman|first4=Jay G.|date=2009-05-30|title=Prevalence of child marriage and its effect on fertility and fertility-control outcomes of young women in India: a cross-sectional, observational study|journal=Lancet|volume=373|issue=9678|pages=1883\u20131889|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(09)60246-4|issn=1474-547X|pmc=2759702|pmid=19278721}}</ref> intimate partner violence<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Silverman|first=Jay G.|last2=Decker|first2=Michele R.|last3=Reed|first3=Elizabeth|last4=Raj|first4=Anita|date=2006\u20132007|title=Intimate partner violence victimization prior to and during pregnancy among women residing in 26 U.S. states: associations with maternal and neonatal health|journal=American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology|volume=195|issue=1|pages=140\u2013148|doi=10.1016/j.ajog.2005.12.052|issn=1097-6868|pmid=16813751}}</ref> and sexual assault, and son preference; development and evaluation of HIV,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Amaro|first=Hortensia|last2=Raj|first2=Anita|date=2000|title=On the Margin: Power and Women's HIV Risk Reduction Strategies|journal=Sex Roles|language=en|volume=42|issue=7/8|pages=723\u2013749|doi=10.1023/a:1007059708789|issn=0360-0025}}</ref> unintended pregnancy, and gender-based violence prevention interventions in low resource settings with socially vulnerable populations including minorities, people contending with problem substance use, and youth; and application of social and behavioral theories, including gender theories for measurement development and evaluation research. She is well-known for her child marriage work in South Asia. In 2014 she was an invited panelist, asked to speak on child, early and forced marriage at the [[United Nations General Assembly]] in New York, NY.\n\n=== Media ===\nRaj's work has been covered by popular media including the ''[[New York Times]], [[NPR]],'' the ''[[New York Post]]'', and ''[[USA Today]]''.\n\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/21/upshot/pervasive-sexual-harassment-why-me-too-took-off-poll.html \"Pervasive Sexual Harassment Why #MeToo Took Off Poll\" - ''New York Times'']\n*[https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2017/12/03/567726950/how-chickens-and-goats-are-helping-to-stop-child-marriage \"How Chickens and Goats Are Helping to Stop Child Marriage\" - ''NPR, Goats and Soda'']\n*[https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/02/21/587671849/a-new-survey-finds-eighty-percent-of-women-have-experienced-sexual-harassment \"A New Survey Finds Eighty-Percent of Women Have Experienced Sexual Harassment\" - ''NPR, The Two Way'']\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=193475321 \"WHO Finds Violence Against Women in 'Shockingly' Common\" - ''NPR, Shots'']\n*[https://nypost.com/2018/02/21/nearly-all-hollywood-women-say-theyve-been-sexually-harassed/ \"Nearly All Hollywood Women Say They've Been Sexually Harassed\" - ''New York Post'']\n*[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2016/05/160511154154.htm \"Modern Family Planning In India\" - ''Science Daily'']\n*[https://www.asianscientist.com/2012/05/features/jama-study-child-marriages-india-nepal-pakistan-bangladesh-2012/ \"Jama Study Child Marriages India, Nepal, Pakistan, Bangladesh\" - ''Asian Scientist'']\n*[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/02/20/how-common-sexual-misconduct-hollywood/1083964001/ \"How Common Sexual Misconduct in Hollywood\" - ''USA Today'']\n*[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/tata-trusts--university-of-california-san-diego-partner-to-establish-tata-institute-for-active-genetics-and-society-tiags-300349396.html \"Tata Trusts and University of California San Diego partner to establish Tata Institute for Active Genetics and Society (TIAGS)\" - ''PR Newswire, Cision'']\n\n=== Publications ===\n\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Raj | first1 = A | last2 = Saggurti | first2 = N | last3 = Balaiah | first3 = D | last4 = Silverman | first4 = JG | year = 2009 | title = Prevalence of child marriage and its effect on fertility and fertility-control outcomes of young women in India: a cross-sectional, observational study | journal = Lancet | volume = 373 | issue = 9678| pages = 1883\u20139 | pmid = 19278721 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(09)60246-4 | pmc = 2759702 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Raj | first1 = A | year = 2010 | title = When the mother is a child: the impact of child marriage on the health and human rights of girls | url = | journal = Archives of Disease in Childhood | volume = 95 | issue = 11| pages = 931\u20135 | pmid = 20930011 | doi = 10.1136/adc.2009.178707 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Amaro | first1 = H | last2 = Raj | first2 = A | year = 2000 | title = On the Margin: Power and Women's HIV Risk Reduction Strategies | url = https://link.springer.com/article/10.1023/A:1007059708789 | journal = Sex Roles | volume = 42 | issue = 7| pages = 723\u201349 | doi = 10.1023/A:1007059708789 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Raj | first1 = A | last2 = Silverman | first2 = JG | year = 2002 | title = Violence against immigrant women: The roles of culture, context, and legal status on intimate partner violence | url = http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/10778010222183107 | journal = Violence Against Women | volume = 8 | issue = 3| pages = 367\u201398 | doi = 10.1177/10778010222183107 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Silverman | first1 = JG | last2 = Decker | first2 = MR | last3 = Reed | first3 = E | last4 = Raj | first4 = A | year = 2006 | title = Intimate partner violence victimization prior to and during pregnancy among women residing in 26 US states: associations with maternal and neonatal health | journal = American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology | volume = 195 | issue = 1| pages = 140\u20138 | pmid = 16813751 | doi = 10.1016/j.ajog.2005.12.052 }}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Scholia|author}}\n* [https://medschool.ucsd.edu/som/medicine/divisions/infectious-diseases/Pages/default.aspx UCSD Division of Infectious Disease and Global Public Health] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190529191556/http://geh.ucsd.edu/ UCSD Center on Gender Equity & Health]\n*[https://twitter.com/anitarajucsd?lang=en Twitter - Anita Raj]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raj, Anita}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women psychologists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Jackson, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Mississippi College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Georgia alumni]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=July 2018}}\n{{COI|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Anita Raj\n| image = \n| image_size = 251px\n| caption = Anita Raj\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|12|29}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = [[United States]]\n| citizenship = [[United States|American]]\n| fields = [[Child Marriage]] <br /> [[Intimate Partner Violence]] <br /> [[Reproductive Health]] <br /> [[Substance abuse]] <br /> [[Sexual Violence]