back and Mike Cosentino\n|-\n|Game Accessory of the Year\n|[[The 13th Hour]] - Roleplaying Soundtrack\n|[[Midnight Syndicate]] Soundtracks\n|Edward Douglas and Gavin Goszka\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Vanguard Innovative Game Awards\n|[[Darter (board game)|Darter]]\n|Future Magic Games\n|Jason Conkey and Dove Byrne\n|-\n|[[PerplexCity: The Boardgame|Perplex City]]\n|[[Mind Candy (company)|Mind Candy]]\n|Michael Smith and Adrian Hon\n|-\n|[[Polarity (game)|Polarity]]\n|Temple Games, Inc.\n|Doug Seaton\n|-\n|[[XIG: The Four Elements]]\n|GT2 Fun & Games Inc.\n|Greg Scott, Greg Waring,Tor Nawrot, and Tim Huesken\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Vanguard Unique Game Awards\n|[[Battleground: Fantasy Warfare]]\n|Your Move Games, Inc.\n|Robert Dougherty and Chad Ellis\n|-\n|[[Infinite Armies]]\n|[[Blacksburg Tactical Research Center|BTRC]]\n|Greg Porter\n|-\n|[[Rocketmen|Rocketmen: Axis of Evil]]\n|[[WizKids]]\n|Jordan Weisman, Jon Leitheusser, and Shane Small\n|-\n|World at War\n|Matrix Games\n|Gary Grigsby\n|-\n|Gamer's Choice Best Board Game of the Year\n|[[Shadows Over Camelot]]\n|[[Days of Wonder]]\n|Authors: Bruno Cathala and Serge Lage\nIllustration and Graphic Design: Cyrille Daujean and Julien Delval\n|-\n|Gamer's Choice Best Collectible Card Game of the Year\n|[[Anachronism (game)|Anachronism]]\n|TriKing Games\n|Michael Brown\n|-\n|Gamer's Choice Best Traditional Card Game of the Year\n|[[Paranoia: The Mandatory Card Game]]\n|[[Mongoose Publishing]]\n|Steve Gilbert\n|-\n|Gamer's Choice Best Historical Game of the Year\n|[[Axis & Allies Miniatures|Axis and Allies Collectible Miniatures Game]]\n|Avalon Hill / Wizards of the Coast\n|[[Richard Baker (game designer)|Richard Baker]] (lead), Paul Barclay, Aaron Forsythe, Devin Low, and Jonathan Tweet\n|-\n|Gamer's Choice Best Role Playing Game of the Year\n|[[Serenity (role-playing game)|Serenity]]\n|[[Margaret Weis Productions, Ltd]]\n|[[Jamie Chambers]]\n|-\n|Gamer's Choice Best Miniatures of the Year\n|WARMACHINE: Apotheosis\n|Privateer Press, Inc.\n|[[Matt Wilson (artist)|Matt Wilson]], Jason Soles, and Rob Stoddard\n|}\n\n==Hall of Fame inductees==\n* [[Aaron Allston]]\n* [[Jolly R. Blackburn]]\n* [[Rodger MacGowan]]\n* [[Dennis Mize]] (posthumous)\n* [[Mike Pondsmith]]\n* [[James Ernest]]\n\n==Hall of Fame Game inductees==\n* [[Star Fleet Battles]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060810185052/http://originsgames.com/awards 2005 Origins Awards]\n* [http://aagad.originsgames.com/aagad/2005-hof-inductees2 2005 and Hall of Fame Inductees]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Origins Awards}}\n\n[[Category:2005 awards]]\n[[Category:Origins Award winners| ]]\n", "text_old": "The following are the winners of the 32nd annual [[Origins Award]], held in 2006:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Category\n! Winner\n! Company\n! Designer(s)\n|-\n|Game of the Year\n|[[Warmachine: Apotheosis|WARMACHINE: Apotheosis]]\n|[[Privateer Press]], Inc.\n|[[Matt Wilson (artist)|Matt Wilson]], Jason Soles, and Rob Stoddard\n|-\n|Board Game of the Year\n|[[Parthenon: Rise of the Aegean]]\n|Siren Bridge Publishing, Inc. & Z-Man Games, Inc\n|Andrew Parks and Jason Hawkins\n|-\n|Collectible Card Game or Expansion of the Year\n|[[Ravnica|Ravnica: City of Guilds]] expansion for [[Magic: The Gathering]]\n|[[Wizards of the Coast]]\n|Mark Rosewater, Aaron Forsythe, Tyler Bielman, [[Richard Garfield]], and Mike Elliott\n|-\n|Traditional Card Game of the Year\n|[[Gloom (card game)|Gloom]]\n|[[Atlas Games]]\n|[[Keith Baker (game designer)|Keith Baker]]\n|-\n|Role-Playing Game of the Year\n|[[Artesia: Adventures in the Known World|Artesia]]\n|Archaia Studios Press\n|[[Mark Smylie]]\n|-\n|Role-Playing Game Supplement of the Year\n|[[GURPS Infinite Worlds]] 4th Edition\n|[[Steve Jackson Games]]\n|[[Kenneth Hite]], [[Steve Jackson (US)|Steve Jackson]], and John M. Ford\n|-\n|Miniatures Game or Expansion of the Year\n|[[All Things Zombie|ATZ - All Things Zombie]]\n|Two Hour Wargames\n|Ed Teixeira\n|-\n|Miniatures of the Year\n|[[WarGods of \u00c6gyptus|Wargods of Aegyptus]]\n|Crocodile Games\n|Chris FitzPatrick\n|-\n|Historical Board Game of the Year\n|[[Lock 'n Load: Band of Heroes|Lock \u2018N Load: Band of Heroes]]\n|Matrix Games\n|Mark H. Walker\n|-\n|Historical Miniature Game or Expansion of the Year\n|[[Gutshot (miniatures game)|Gutshot]]\n|Hawgleg Publishing\n|Mike Mitchell, Mike Murphy and Paul Mauer\n|-\n|Historical Miniatures of the Year\n|10mm WWII Personality Set\n|Game Figures, Inc\n|David Higgs\n|-\n|Nonfiction Publication of the Year\n|[[Historical Miniature Gamer Magazine]]\n|Legio X, Inc.\n|Kathy Plamback and Mike Cosentino\n|-\n|Game Accessory of the Year\n|[[The 13th Hour]] - Roleplaying Soundtrack\n|[[Midnight Syndicate]] Soundtracks\n|Edward Douglas and Gavin Goszka\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Vanguard Innovative Game Awards\n|[[Darter (board game)|Darter]]\n|Future Magic Games\n|Jason Conkey and Dove Byrne\n|-\n|[[PerplexCity: The Boardgame|Perplex City]]\n|[[Mind Candy (company)|Mind Candy]]\n|Michael Smith and Adrian Hon\n|-\n|[[Polarity (game)|Polarity]]\n|Temple Games, Inc.\n|Doug Seaton\n|-\n|[[XIG: The Four Elements]]\n|GT2 Fun & Games Inc.\n|Greg Scott, Greg Waring,Tor Nawrot, and Tim Huesken\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |Vanguard Unique Game Awards\n|[[Battleground: Fantasy Warfare]]\n|Your Move Games, Inc.\n|Robert Dougherty and Chad Ellis\n|-\n|[[Infinite Armies]]\n|[[Blacksburg Tactical Research Center|BTRC]]\n|Greg Porter\n|-\n|[[Rocketmen|Rocketmen: Axis of Evil]]\n|[[WizKids]]\n|Jordan Weisman, Jon Leitheusser, and Shane Small\n|-\n|World at War\n|Matrix Games\n|Gary Grigsby\n|-\n|Gamer\u2019s Choice Best Board Game of the Year\n|[[Shadows Over Camelot]]\n|[[Days of Wonder]]\n|Authors: Bruno Cathala and Serge Lage\nIllustration and Graphic Design: Cyrille Daujean and Julien Delval\n|-\n|Gamer\u2019s Choice Best Collectible Card Game of the Year\n|[[Anachronism (game)|Anachronism]]\n|TriKing Games\n|Michael Brown\n|-\n|Gamer\u2019s Choice Best Traditional Card Game of the Year\n|[[Paranoia: The Mandatory Card Game]]\n|[[Mongoose Publishing]]\n|Steve Gilbert\n|-\n|Gamer\u2019s Choice Best Historical Game of the Year\n|[[Axis & Allies Miniatures|Axis and Allies Collectible Miniatures Game]]\n|Avalon Hill / Wizards of the Coast\n|[[Richard Baker (game designer)|Richard Baker]] (lead), Paul Barclay, Aaron Forsythe, Devin Low, and Jonathan Tweet\n|-\n|Gamer\u2019s Choice Best Role Playing Game of the Year\n|[[Serenity (role-playing game)|Serenity]]\n|[[Margaret Weis Productions, Ltd]]\n|[[Jamie Chambers]]\n|-\n|Gamer\u2019s Choice Best Miniatures of the Year\n|WARMACHINE: Apotheosis\n|Privateer Press, Inc.\n|[[Matt Wilson (artist)|Matt Wilson]], Jason Soles, and Rob Stoddard\n|}\n\n==Hall of Fame inductees==\n* [[Aaron Allston]]\n* [[Jolly R. Blackburn]]\n* [[Rodger MacGowan]]\n* [[Dennis Mize]] (posthumous)\n* [[Mike Pondsmith]]\n* [[James Ernest]]\n\n==Hall of Fame Game inductees==\n* [[Star Fleet Battles]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060810185052/http://originsgames.com/awards 2005 Origins Awards]\n* [http://aagad.originsgames.com/aagad/2005-hof-inductees2 2005 and Hall of Fame Inductees]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n\n{{Origins Awards}}\n\n[[Category:2005 awards]]\n[[Category:Origins Award winners| ]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_Origins_Award_winners"}
{"title_page": "Czech architecture", "text_new": "[[File:Kubistick\u00e1 lampa na Jugmanov\u011b n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed.jpg|thumb|Cubist lamp by [[Emil Kr\u00e1l\u00ed\u010dek]], Jungmannovo n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed, next to the Gothic [[Church of Our Lady of the Snows (Prague)|Church of Our Lady of the Snows]] ([[Prague]])]]\n'''Czech architecture''', or more precisely '''architecture of the [[Czech Republic]]''', is a term covering many important historical and contemporary architectural movements in [[Bohemia]], [[Moravia]], and [[Silesia]]. From its early beginnings to the present day, almost all historical styles are represented, including many monuments from various historical periods. Some of them are [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Czech Republic|UNESCO World Heritage Sites]].\n\n== Gothic ==\n{{main|Czech Gothic architecture}}\n\n== Renaissance ==\n{{main|Czech Renaissance architecture}}\n\n== Baroque ==\n{{main|Czech Baroque architecture}}\n\n== Classicism ==\nAlthough [[Rococo|late Baroque]] in the Czech lands is mainly associated with the reign of [[Maria Theresa]] (1740-1780), after her death, this style was more and more often replaced by [[Neoclassical architecture|classicism]], and ultimately by [[Empire style|imperial style]]. The transition from Baroque to [[Classicism]] is announced by the reconstruction of [[Prague Castle]] by the Viennese architect [[Nicolo Pacassi]]. He and [[Kilian Ignaz Dientzenhofer|Kili\u00e1n Ign\u00e1c Dientzenhofer]] were followed by [[Ign\u00e1c Jan Nepomuk Palliardi]], in whom the already high Baroque tradition is combined with Classicist decor. [[Anton\u00edn Haffenecker]], another architect who went from Baroque to Classicism ([[Estates Theatre]]), is associated with [[Nicol\u00f2 Pacassi|Pacassi]] and [[Johann Bernhard Fischer von Erlach|Johann Bernhard Fischer]].\n\nIn the entire [[Austrian Empire]], i.e. in the Czech lands, there were no suitable conditions for the equally successful development of classical architecture as in [[French architecture|France]] or [[Russian architecture|Russia]]. In the Czech Republic, it is difficult to find a building from the early Classicist period. The reason for the slow development was the ideals of the Enlightenment, which were more restrictive of the old than the new. \n\nDuring Maria Theresa's reign, compulsory schooling was introduced, which clearly contributed to the education of the empire's population. Her son, [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Joseph II]], initiated the so-called [[Josephinism|Josephine reforms]], during which hundreds of churches and monasteries were abolished throughout the Empire, entire orders were dissolved, and the abandoned buildings were transformed into offices, public hospitals or barracks. In Austria the [[bourgeoisie]] developed slowly, which was not strong enough to push through the changes and put an end to [[Feudalism in the Holy Roman Empire|feudalism]] because it feared the atrocities that took place in [[French Revolution|revolutionary France]]. That's why classicism in the Czech lands was lagging behind and manifested itself sporadically in less important buildings. \n[[File:Schloss-Kolosoruk-1.jpg|thumb|[[Korozluky]] Castle]]\nThe evolution of Classicism from the Baroque period is quite evident, as figurative ornaments are gradually being abandoned and the richness of the ornamentation gives way to late Classicism buildings, which have been transformed into strict empire-building lines.\n\nExamples might include [[Duchcov Chateau]], [[Karlova Koruna Chateau]], [[Kyn\u017evart Castle]].\n\n== Empire style ==\n[[File:Z\u00e1mek Ka\u010dina - 01.jpg|thumb|[[Ka\u010dina]] Castle in Chotkov]]\nThe period of [[Empire style|imperial style]] is mainly associated with the [[First French Empire]] under Napoleon I. \n{{main|Empire style}}\nTypical for Empire buildings are clean, regular shapes with minimal decoration, lines are straight to raw. The main feature of Empire architecture is a frequent use of characteristic columns and triangular facades of larger buildings.\n\nThe most important building in the Empire style is [[Ka\u010dina|Ka\u010dina Chotkov Castle]], but also interesting are Fry\u0161t\u00e1t (Lottyhaus) castle in [[Karvin\u00e1]], Boskovice, Pohansko ([[Lednice\u2013Valtice Cultural Landscape]]) and [[Kostelec nad Orlic\u00ed]] Castle. An interesting example of the transition from classicism to the Empire style is the new chateau in [[Da\u010dice]].\n\n== Modern period ==\n\n=== Secession ===\nThe wave of [[Art Nouveau]] at the turn of the 19th and 20th centuries was significant in Czech architecture. Typical are Art Nouveau buildings, especially as private villas, hotels or public buildings (town hall, schools, crematoria), as well as several churches or castle buildings.\n[[Image:Jugendstil Prag Gemeindehaus 1.jpg|thumb|[[Municipal House]]]]\n\nThe most important Czech architects of this period are [[Anton\u00edn Bal\u0161\u00e1nek]], [[Osvald Pol\u00edvka]], [[Josef Fanta]], [[Jan Letzel]], [[Alphonse Mucha|Alfons Mucha]].\n\nImportant monuments include [[Municipal House]], [[Vr\u0161ovice Savings Bank Building]], [[Praha hlavn\u00ed n\u00e1dra\u017e\u00ed]], [[Brno hlavn\u00ed n\u00e1dra\u017e\u00ed]], [[Villa B\u00edlek]], [[\u0160aloun Villa]], [[Hotel Paris (Prague)]], [[Vinohrady Theatre]], [[J. K. Tyl Theatre]], [[City of Prague Museum]].\n\n=== Cubism ===\n{{main|Czech cubism}}\n[[File:Prag Kubismus Schwarze Madonna 1.jpg|thumb|left|[[House of the Black Madonna]]]]\nCubism appeared at the beginning of the 20th century as an avant-garde artistic movement based on completely new ideas. The term \"[[Cubism]]\" was first used by the French art critic [[Louis Vauxcelles]] in 1908.\nThe principle of Cubism is based on the [[Spatial analysis|spatial]] concept of a work of art, in which it captures objects not only from one angle but from several angles at once. The presented object has been distributed into basic geometric shapes (mainly [[Cube|cubes]]). Therefore, Cubism had to solve new problems of perspective and create new spatial relations between the objects. Three-dimensional objects created many views with unusual angles.[[File:Czech-03841 - Cubist Building (32865168462).jpg|thumb|Cubist architecture in Prague]]\nCubism directly or indirectly influenced the development of new artistic styles ([[futurism]], [[Constructivism (art)|constructivism]], and [[expressionism]]). However, unlike other movements, Cubism had no expression in literature. It manifested itself mainly in painting, sculpture, and partly also in the architecture of the former [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]], where it became an independent artistic style.\n[[File:D\u016fm_U_\u010dern\u00e9_Matky_Bo\u017e\u00ed_kav\u00e1rna_2.jpg|thumb|Grand Caf\u00e9 Orient in Prague]]\nCubism manifested itself primarily in the fine arts ([[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]], [[Georges Braque|Braque]], [[Paul C\u00e9zanne|C\u00e9zanne]]), which strongly influenced some architects, but one cannot speak of pure cubism, because of course, they had to be primarily functional. The architects working under the influence of Cubism created characteristic objects that seem a bit strange. Cubist architecture in Czechoslovakia has been operating since around 1911. In the 1920s, it developed in Prague. Its most prominent representatives gathered in the Manes Fine Arts Association. They include painters [[Emil Filla]], [[Anton\u00edn Proch\u00e1zka (painter)|Anton\u00edn Proch\u00e1zka]] and [[Josef \u010capek]], sculptor [[Otto Gutfreund]],  architects [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]], [[Josef Chochol]], [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]], and others. \n\nThe Cubist style is unique in the world and nowhere else has Cubist architecture reached such a boom as in the Czech Republic.\n\nArchitects:\n\n* [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]]\n* [[Josef Chochol]]\n* [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]]\n* [[Otakar Novotn\u00fd]]\n* [[Vlastislav Hofman]]\n\n=== Rondocubism ===\n[[Rondocubism]] is an independent local formula of Czech architecture. It developed as an independent branch of the Cubist style after World War I in the newly established [[Czechoslovakia]], where it became the national style for a short time. \n[[File:Prague Cubim Adria Palace.jpg|thumb|Adria Palace (Prague)]]\nRondocubism, as the name suggests, is characterized by the use of round shapes such as arches, circles, and ovals, which are based on Cubist foundations. These were to commemorate national [[List of Slavic cultures|Slavic traditions]]. Rondocubism was most evident in Prague, but also in other places, especially in the form of industrial architecture. The highest buildings in the world of Rondocubism are considered to be [[Legiobanka]] by [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]] and Adria Palace by [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]] in Prague.\n\nRondo-Cubism has also manifested itself in art, for example in the paintings of [[Josef \u010capek|Josef \u010cape]]<nowiki/>k and Objectdesign. Furniture created by [[Bohumil Waigant]] and Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r is still preserved.\n\nRondocubism in architecture tried to contain characteristic Slavic elements. The use of national colors: red and white should also help. The shapes of rondocubist buildings are usually massive, cylindrical, round, similar to annual wooden rings.\n\nThe seat of the Legiobanka in Na Po\u0159\u00ed\u010d\u00ed Street is a rondocubist monument from 1921-1923. Its facade was decorated by [[Otto Gutfreund]] and [[Jan \u0160tursa]]. The stained-glass windows in the hall and decorative bricks are the work of [[Franti\u0161ek Kysel]].\n\nThe Adria Palace, built in 1925 by Pavel Jan\u00e1k and German architect Josef Zasch from Prague, on Jungmann Square for the Italian insurance company Riunione Adriatica di Sicurt\u00e0. The sculptural decoration is the work of [[Jan \u0160tursa]] and Karl Dvo\u0159\u00e1k. In 1926, during a conference in Prague, when the French architect [[Le Corbusier]] saw the Adria Palace, he called it \"a massive structure with an [[Assyria|Assyrian]] appearance\".\n\nThe Rondocubist furniture in the house on Kamenick\u00e1 Street in [[Hole\u0161ovice]] is the work of Otakar Novotny.\n\n=== Functionalism ===\n[[File:Brno, Lipov\u00e1.jpg|thumb|left|Semi-detached villa in [[Brno]] by [[Otto Eisler]], according to [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]]'s [[Henry-Russell Hitchcock]] and [[Philip Johnson]], is a defining building of the [[International Style (architecture)|International style]].]]\n[[Functionalism (architecture)|Functionalist]] [[Villa Tugendhat]] is one of the most famous examples of Czech architecture of the 20th century and is a [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage Site]].\n[[File:Praha,_Spo\u0159ilov,_kostel_sv._Ane\u017eky_-_v\u011b\u017e.jpg|thumb|Church of Saint Agnes of Bohemia (Spo\u0159ilov)]]\nSince the 1920s, architecture has been striving for functionalism, an architectural style that primarily applies the criteria of functionality, usability and practical purpose. This direction is guided by the motto \"form follows function\", which in practice manifests itself in simple, sometimes even austere lines.\n\nThe main representatives of this direction in the Czech lands were architects [[Jan Kot\u011bra]] and [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]], as well as the prominent [[Architecture of Slovenia|Slovenian]] architect [[Jo\u017ee Ple\u010dnik|Josip Ple\u010dnik]]. He was the author of the [[Church of the Most Sacred Heart of Our Lord|Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus]] in Prague. Another important foreign architect working in Czechoslovakia was [[Ludwig Mies van der Rohe]], author of ''Villa Tugendhat''.\n\nImportant monuments include: [[National Gallery Prague]], [[Ba\u0165a's Skyscraper]], [[Tomas Bata Memorial]], [[Barrandov Terraces]], [[Hus Congregational House]], [[Agudas Achim Synagogue (Brno)]], [[Sm\u00edchov Synagogue]].\n\n== Late and postmodernism ==\n\n=== Socialist realism ===\nIn the 1950s [[socialist realism]] (also called sorela) was required as an official style. Characteristic buildings in its spirit are the Jalta Hotel on [[Wenceslas Square]] or the [[Poruba (Ostrava)|Poruba]] housing estate in [[Ostrava]]. A specific branch of Sorela was the so-called [[Stalinist architecture|Stalinist neoclassicism]], which represents [[Hotel International Prague|Hotel International]] in Prague's [[Dejvice]].\n\n=== Brussels style ===\nHowever, in the late 1950s, the new style, known as \"Brussels\", became popular in architecture (and of course in design), as it was presented at [[Expo 58]] in [[Brussels]]. It was characterized by round shapes and glass facades. A typical building in the Brussels style was the Czech Expo pavilion (no longer existing) and the building of the Czech restaurant (currently in [[Letn\u00e1 Park]], Prague). Other important buildings in the Brussels style are the Z pavilion in the [[Brno Exhibition Centre|exhibition center in Brno]], the [[Podol\u00ed Swimming Stadium|swimming pool in Podol\u00ed]] and the [[Hav\u00ed\u0159ov railway station|railway station]] in [[Hav\u00ed\u0159ov]].\n\n=== Czech brutalism ===\n[[File:Transgas II., model.jpg|thumb|[[Transgas (building)]]]]\nIn the late 1960s, the Czech version of [[Brutalist architecture|brutalism]] replaced the Brussels style. The projects of [[V\u011bra Machoninov\u00e1]] and her husband Vladim\u00edr Machon\u00edn (residential community center in Prague, Hotel Thermal in [[Karlovy Vary]], [[Kotva Department Store|Kotva]] in Prague, the Czechoslovak embassy in Berlin) are particularly appreciated. \n\nOther buildings include the [[Embassy of the Czech Republic, London|Czechoslovak embassy in London]] (architects [[Jan Bo\u010dan]], Jan \u0160r\u00e1mek and [[Karel \u0160t\u011bp\u00e1nsk\u00fd]]), the [[Hotel InterContinental Prague|Intercontinental Hotel]] (Karel Buben\u00ed\u010dek and Karel Filsak), [[Karel Prager]] buildings (former [[Federal Assembly (Czechoslovakia)|Federal Assembly building]], New Stage of the [[National Theatre (Prague)|National Theatre]]). However, the most valued building of that time was a transmitter and hotel on [[Je\u0161t\u011bd Tower|Je\u0161t\u011bd]], by [[Karel Hub\u00e1\u010dek]].\n\n=== Postmodern architecture ===\nThe [[Dancing House]] of Frank Gehry and Vlado Milu\u0148 in Prague, which was initiated directly by [[V\u00e1clav Havel]], is often referred to as a symbol of [[Postmodern architecture|post-modern architecture]]. [[Jean Nouvel]] ([[Golden Angel]] in Prague's [[Sm\u00edchov|Smichov]]) or [[Ricardo Bofill]] were among the most important architects in Prague at that time. \n\nOthers include the project of transforming the [[Central Business District Praha|surroundings of the Masaryk station]], which was prepared by the [[Pritzker Architecture Prize|Pritzker Prize]] winner [[Zaha Hadid]]. Among other projects, the [[Czech National Library of Technology|National Technical Library]] in Prague's [[Dejvice]] district received the greatest recognition. The widely discussed design of the new building of the [[National Library of the Czech Republic|National Library]] of [[Jan Kaplick\u00fd|Jan Kaplicky]] remained only on paper. Among the successful contemporary Czech architects is [[Eva Ji\u0159i\u010dn\u00e1]], who designed, for example, the Orangery at Prague Castle, Zl\u00edn Congress Centre and other buildings abroad.\n\n==Literature and sources==\n* \u010cERN\u00c1, Marie. D\u011bjiny v\u00fdtvarn\u00e9ho um\u011bn\u00ed. Praha: IDEA SERVIS, 2012. {{ISBN|978-80-85970-74-6}}. S. 91-93.\n* \u0160AM\u00c1NKOV\u00c1, Eva. Architektura \u010desk\u00e9 renesance. Praha: St\u00e1tn\u00ed nakladatelstv\u00ed kr\u00e1sn\u00e9 literatury a um\u011bn\u00ed, 1961.\n* D\u011bjiny \u010desk\u00e9ho v\u00fdtvarn\u00e9ho um\u011bn\u00ed II/1. Academia, Praha 1989. {{ISBN|80-200-0069-0}}\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscat-inline|Architecture of the Czech Republic}}\t\n<!--spacing-->\n{{Czech Republic topics}}\n{{Architecture of Europe}}\n{{Archhistory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Czech Architecture}}\n[[Category:Architecture of the Czech Republic| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kubistick\u00e1 lampa na Jugmanov\u011b n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed.jpg|thumb|Cubist lamp by [[Emil Kr\u00e1l\u00ed\u010dek]], Jungmannovo n\u00e1m\u011bst\u00ed, next to the Gothic [[Church of Our Lady of the Snows (Prague)|Church of Our Lady of the Snows]] ([[Prague]])]]\n'''Czech architecture''', or more precisely '''architecture of the [[Czech Republic]]''', is a term covering many important historical and contemporary architectural movements in [[Bohemia]], [[Moravia]], and [[Silesia]]. From its early beginnings to the present day, almost all historical styles are represented, including many monuments from various historical periods. Some of them are [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Czech Republic|UNESCO World Heritage Sites]].\n\n== Gothic ==\n{{main|Czech Gothic architecture}}\n\n== Renaissance ==\n{{main|Czech Renaissance architecture}}\n\n== Baroque ==\n{{main|Czech Baroque architecture}}\n\n== Classicism ==\nAlthough [[Rococo|late Baroque]] in the Czech lands is mainly associated with the reign of [[Maria Theresa]] (1740-1780), after her death, this style was more and more often replaced by [[Neoclassical architecture|classicism]], and ultimately by [[Empire style|imperial style]]. The transition from Baroque to [[Classicism]] is announced by the reconstruction of [[Prague Castle]] by the Viennese architect [[Nicolo Pacassi]]. He and [[Kilian Ignaz Dientzenhofer|Kili\u00e1n Ign\u00e1c Dientzenhofer]] were followed by [[Ign\u00e1c Jan Nepomuk Palliardi]], in whom the already high Baroque tradition is combined with Classicist decor. [[Anton\u00edn Haffenecker]], another architect who went from Baroque to Classicism ([[Estates Theatre]]), is associated with [[Nicol\u00f2 Pacassi|Pacassi]] and [[Johann Bernhard Fischer von Erlach|Johann Bernhard Fischer]].\n\nIn the entire [[Austrian Empire]], i.e. in the Czech lands, there were no suitable conditions for the equally successful development of classical architecture as in [[French architecture|France]] or [[Russian architecture|Russia]]. In the Czech Republic, it is difficult to find a building from the early Classicist period. The reason for the slow development was the ideals of the Enlightenment, which were more restrictive of the old than the new. \n\nDuring Maria Theresa's reign, compulsory schooling was introduced, which clearly contributed to the education of the empire's population. Her son, [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Joseph II]], initiated the so-called [[Josephinism|Josephine reforms]], during which hundreds of churches and monasteries were abolished throughout the Empire, entire orders were dissolved, and the abandoned buildings were transformed into offices, public hospitals or barracks. In Austria the [[bourgeoisie]] developed slowly, which was not strong enough to push through the changes and put an end to [[Feudalism in the Holy Roman Empire|feudalism]] because it feared the atrocities that took place in [[French Revolution|revolutionary France]]. That's why classicism in the Czech lands was lagging behind and manifested itself sporadically in less important buildings. \n[[File:Schloss-Kolosoruk-1.jpg|thumb|[[Korozluky]] Castle]]\nThe evolution of Classicism from the Baroque period is quite evident, as figurative ornaments are gradually being abandoned and the richness of the ornamentation gives way to late Classicism buildings, which have been transformed into strict empire-building lines.\n\nExamples might include [[Duchcov Chateau]], [[Karlova Koruna Chateau]], [[Kyn\u017evart Castle]].\n\n== Empire style ==\n[[File:Z\u00e1mek Ka\u010dina - 01.jpg|thumb|[[Ka\u010dina]] Castle in Chotkov]]\nThe period of [[Empire style|imperial style]] is mainly associated with the [[First French Empire]] under Napoleon I. \n{{main|Empire style}}\nTypical for Empire buildings are clean, regular shapes with minimal decoration, lines are straight to raw. The main feature of Empire architecture is a frequent use of characteristic columns and triangular facades of larger buildings.\n\nThe most important building in the Empire style is [[Ka\u010dina|Ka\u010dina Chotkov Castle]], but also interesting are Fry\u0161t\u00e1t (Lottyhaus) castle in [[Karvin\u00e1]], Boskovice, Pohansko ([[Lednice\u2013Valtice Cultural Landscape]]) and [[Kostelec nad Orlic\u00ed]] Castle. An interesting example of the transition from classicism to the Empire style is the new chateau in [[Da\u010dice]].\n\n== Modern period ==\n\n=== Secession ===\nThe wave of [[Art Nouveau]] at the turn of the 19th and 20th centuries was significant in Czech architecture. Typical are Art Nouveau buildings, especially as private villas, hotels or public buildings (town hall, schools, crematoria), as well as several churches or castle buildings.\n[[Image:Jugendstil Prag Gemeindehaus 1.jpg|thumb|[[Municipal House]]]]\n\nThe most important Czech architects of this period are [[Anton\u00edn Bal\u0161\u00e1nek]], [[Osvald Pol\u00edvka]], [[Josef Fanta]], [[Jan Letzel]], [[Alphonse Mucha|Alfons Mucha]].\n\nImportant monuments include [[Municipal House]], [[Vr\u0161ovice Savings Bank Building]], [[Praha hlavn\u00ed n\u00e1dra\u017e\u00ed]], [[Brno hlavn\u00ed n\u00e1dra\u017e\u00ed]], [[Villa B\u00edlek]], [[\u0160aloun Villa]], [[Hotel Paris (Prague)]], [[Vinohrady Theatre]], [[J. K. Tyl Theatre]], [[City of Prague Museum]].\n\n=== Cubism ===\n{{main|Czech cubism}}\n[[File:Prag Kubismus Schwarze Madonna 1.jpg|thumb|left|[[House of the Black Madonna]]]]\nCubism appeared at the beginning of the 20th century as an avant-garde artistic movement based on completely new ideas. The term \"[[Cubism]]\" was first used by the French art critic [[Louis Vauxcelles]] in 1908.\nThe principle of Cubism is based on the [[Spatial analysis|spatial]] concept of a work of art, in which it captures objects not only from one angle but from several angles at once. The presented object has been distributed into basic geometric shapes (mainly [[Cube|cubes]]). Therefore, Cubism had to solve new problems of perspective and create new spatial relations between the objects. Three-dimensional objects created many views with unusual angles.[[File:Czech-03841 - Cubist Building (32865168462).jpg|thumb|Cubist architecture in Prague]]\nCubism directly or indirectly influenced the development of new artistic styles ([[futurism]], [[Constructivism (art)|constructivism]], and [[expressionism]]). However, unlike other movements, Cubism had no expression in literature. It manifested itself mainly in painting, sculpture, and partly also in the architecture of the former [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]], where it became an independent artistic style.\n[[File:D\u016fm_U_\u010dern\u00e9_Matky_Bo\u017e\u00ed_kav\u00e1rna_2.jpg|thumb|Grand Caf\u00e9 Orient in Prague]]\nCubism manifested itself primarily in the fine arts ([[Pablo Picasso|Picasso]], [[Georges Braque|Braque]], [[Paul C\u00e9zanne|C\u00e9zanne]]), which strongly influenced some architects, but one cannot speak of pure cubism, because of course, they had to be primarily functional. The architects working under the influence of Cubism created characteristic objects that seem a bit strange. Cubist architecture in Czechoslovakia has been operating since around 1911. In the 1920s, it developed in Prague. Its most prominent representatives gathered in the Manes Fine Arts Association. They include painters [[Emil Filla]], [[Anton\u00edn Proch\u00e1zka (painter)|Anton\u00edn Proch\u00e1zka]] and [[Josef \u010capek]], sculptor [[Otto Gutfreund]],  architects [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]], [[Josef Chochol]], [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]], and others. \n\nThe Cubist style is unique in the world and nowhere else has Cubist architecture reached such a boom as in the Czech Republic.\n\nArchitects:\n\n* [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]]\n* [[Josef Chochol]]\n* [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]]\n* [[Otakar Novotn\u00fd]]\n* [[Vlastislav Hofman]]\n\n=== Rondocubism ===\n[[Rondocubism]] is an independent local formula of Czech architecture. It developed as an independent branch of the Cubist style after World War I in the newly established [[Czechoslovakia]], where it became the national style for a short time. \n[[File:Prague Cubim Adria Palace.jpg|thumb|Adria Palace (Prague)]]\nRondocubism, as the name suggests, is characterized by the use of round shapes such as arches, circles, and ovals, which are based on Cubist foundations. These were to commemorate national [[List of Slavic cultures|Slavic traditions]]. Rondocubism was most evident in Prague, but also in other places, especially in the form of industrial architecture. The highest buildings in the world of Rondocubism are considered to be [[Legiobanka]] by [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]] and Adria Palace by [[Pavel Jan\u00e1k]] in Prague.\n\nRondo-Cubism has also manifested itself in art, for example in the paintings of [[Josef \u010capek|Josef \u010cape]]<nowiki/>k and Objectdesign. Furniture created by [[Bohumil Waigant]] and Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r is still preserved.\n\nRondocubism in architecture tried to contain characteristic Slavic elements. The use of national colors: red and white should also help. The shapes of rondocubist buildings are usually massive, cylindrical, round, similar to annual wooden rings.\n\nThe seat of the Legiobanka in Na Po\u0159\u00ed\u010d\u00ed Street is a rondocubist monument from 1921-1923. Its facade was decorated by [[Otto Gutfreund]] and [[Jan \u0160tursa]]. The stained-glass windows in the hall and decorative bricks are the work of [[Franti\u0161ek Kysel]].\n\nThe Adria Palace, built in 1925 by Pavel Jan\u00e1k and German architect Josef Zasch from Prague, on Jungmann Square for the Italian insurance company Riunione Adriatica di Sicurt\u00e0. The sculptural decoration is the work of [[Jan \u0160tursa]] and Karl Dvo\u0159\u00e1k. In 1926, during a conference in Prague, when the French architect [[Le Corbusier]] saw the Adria Palace, he called it \"a massive structure with an [[Assyrian]] appearance\".\n\nThe Rondocubist furniture in the house on Kamenick\u00e1 Street in [[Hole\u0161ovice]] is the work of Otakar Novotny.\n\n=== Functionalism ===\n[[File:Brno, Lipov\u00e1.jpg|thumb|left|Semi-detached villa in [[Brno]] by [[Otto Eisler]], according to [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]]'s [[Henry-Russell Hitchcock]] and [[Philip Johnson]], is a defining building of the [[International Style (architecture)|International style]].]]\n[[Functionalism (architecture)|Functionalist]] [[Villa Tugendhat]] is one of the most famous examples of Czech architecture of the 20th century and is a [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage Site]].\n[[File:Praha,_Spo\u0159ilov,_kostel_sv._Ane\u017eky_-_v\u011b\u017e.jpg|thumb|Church of Saint Agnes of Bohemia (Spo\u0159ilov)]]\nSince the 1920s, architecture has been striving for functionalism, an architectural style that primarily applies the criteria of functionality, usability and practical purpose. This direction is guided by the motto \"form follows function\", which in practice manifests itself in simple, sometimes even austere lines.\n\nThe main representatives of this direction in the Czech lands were architects [[Jan Kot\u011bra]] and [[Josef Go\u010d\u00e1r]], as well as the prominent [[Architecture of Slovenia|Slovenian]] architect [[Jo\u017ee Ple\u010dnik|Josip Ple\u010dnik]]. He was the author of the [[Church of the Most Sacred Heart of Our Lord|Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus]] in Prague. Another important foreign architect working in Czechoslovakia was [[Ludwig Mies van der Rohe]], author of ''Villa Tugendhat''.\n\nImportant monuments include: [[National Gallery Prague]], [[Ba\u0165a's Skyscraper]], [[Tomas Bata Memorial]], [[Barrandov Terraces]], [[Hus Congregational House]], [[Agudas Achim Synagogue (Brno)]], [[Sm\u00edchov Synagogue]].\n\n== Late and postmodernism ==\n\n=== Socialist realism ===\nIn the 1950s [[socialist realism]] (also called sorela) was required as an official style. Characteristic buildings in its spirit are the Jalta Hotel on [[Wenceslas Square]] or the [[Poruba (Ostrava)|Poruba]] housing estate in [[Ostrava]]. A specific branch of Sorela was the so-called [[Stalinist architecture|Stalinist neoclassicism]], which represents [[Hotel International Prague|Hotel International]] in Prague's [[Dejvice]].\n\n=== Brussels style ===\nHowever, in the late 1950s, the new style, known as \"Brussels\", became popular in architecture (and of course in design), as it was presented at [[Expo 58]] in [[Brussels]]. It was characterized by round shapes and glass facades. A typical building in the Brussels style was the Czech Expo pavilion (no longer existing) and the building of the Czech restaurant (currently in [[Letn\u00e1 Park]], Prague). Other important buildings in the Brussels style are the Z pavilion in the [[Brno Exhibition Centre|exhibition center in Brno]], the [[Podol\u00ed Swimming Stadium|swimming pool in Podol\u00ed]] and the [[Hav\u00ed\u0159ov railway station|railway station]] in [[Hav\u00ed\u0159ov]].\n\n=== Czech brutalism ===\n[[File:Transgas II., model.jpg|thumb|[[Transgas (building)]]]]\nIn the late 1960s, the Czech version of [[Brutalist architecture|brutalism]] replaced the Brussels style. The projects of [[V\u011bra Machoninov\u00e1]] and her husband Vladim\u00edr Machon\u00edn (residential community center in Prague, Hotel Thermal in [[Karlovy Vary]], [[Kotva Department Store|Kotva]] in Prague, the Czechoslovak embassy in Berlin) are particularly appreciated. \n\nOther buildings include the [[Embassy of the Czech Republic, London|Czechoslovak embassy in London]] (architects [[Jan Bo\u010dan]], Jan \u0160r\u00e1mek and [[Karel \u0160t\u011bp\u00e1nsk\u00fd]]), the [[Hotel InterContinental Prague|Intercontinental Hotel]] (Karel Buben\u00ed\u010dek and Karel Filsak), [[Karel Prager]] buildings (former [[Federal Assembly (Czechoslovakia)|Federal Assembly building]], New Stage of the [[National Theatre (Prague)|National Theatre]]). However, the most valued building of that time was a transmitter and hotel on [[Je\u0161t\u011bd Tower|Je\u0161t\u011bd]], by [[Karel Hub\u00e1\u010dek]].\n\n=== Postmodern architecture ===\nThe [[Dancing House]] of Frank Gehry and Vlado Milu\u0148 in Prague, which was initiated directly by [[V\u00e1clav Havel]], is often referred to as a symbol of [[Postmodern architecture|post-modern architecture]]. [[Jean Nouvel]] ([[Golden Angel]] in Prague's [[Sm\u00edchov|Smichov]]) or [[Ricardo Bofill]] were among the most important architects in Prague at that time. \n\nOthers include the project of transforming the [[Central Business District Praha|surroundings of the Masaryk station]], which was prepared by the [[Pritzker Architecture Prize|Pritzker Prize]] winner [[Zaha Hadid]]. Among other projects, the [[Czech National Library of Technology|National Technical Library]] in Prague's [[Dejvice]] district received the greatest recognition. The widely discussed design of the new building of the [[National Library of the Czech Republic|National Library]] of [[Jan Kaplick\u00fd|Jan Kaplicky]] remained only on paper. Among the successful contemporary Czech architects is [[Eva Ji\u0159i\u010dn\u00e1]], who designed, for example, the Orangery at Prague Castle, Zl\u00edn Congress Centre and other buildings abroad.\n\n==Literature and sources==\n* \u010cERN\u00c1, Marie. D\u011bjiny v\u00fdtvarn\u00e9ho um\u011bn\u00ed. Praha: IDEA SERVIS, 2012. {{ISBN|978-80-85970-74-6}}. S. 91-93.\n* \u0160AM\u00c1NKOV\u00c1, Eva. Architektura \u010desk\u00e9 renesance. Praha: St\u00e1tn\u00ed nakladatelstv\u00ed kr\u00e1sn\u00e9 literatury a um\u011bn\u00ed, 1961.\n* D\u011bjiny \u010desk\u00e9ho v\u00fdtvarn\u00e9ho um\u011bn\u00ed II/1. Academia, Praha 1989. {{ISBN|80-200-0069-0}}\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscat-inline|Architecture of the Czech Republic}}\t\n<!--spacing-->\n{{Czech Republic topics}}\n{{Architecture of Europe}}\n{{Archhistory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Czech Architecture}}\n[[Category:Architecture of the Czech Republic| ]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAssyrian(link changed toAssyria) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Czech_architecture"}
{"title_page": "Richard Friedl\u00e4nder", "text_new": "[[File:Richard Friedl\u00e4nder 1936.JPG|thumb|Richard Friedl\u00e4nder (deceased 1938 at KZ Buchenwald), stepfather of Magda Goebbels]]\n'''Richard Friedl\u00e4nder''' (born February 15, 1881 in Berlin, - February 18, 1939 [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] <ref>Totenbuch KZ Buchenwald [http://totenbuch.buchenwald.de/names/details/person/964/ref/recherche]</ref>) was a German Jewish merchant, adopting father of [[Magda Goebbels]], prisoner in the Buchenwald concentration camp, (prior the WWII [[Holocaust|Holocaust]]).\n\n== Life ==\n\nFriedl\u00e4nder was born to a wealthy Jewish Berlin merchant family. After attending junior high school, he learned the profession of a merchant and later worked as an employee in [[Brussels]]. In 1908 he married Auguste Behrend, who had divorced her first husband Oskar Ritschel, and who brought her only child Magda into the marriage.{{sfn|Meissner|1980|p=16}} Friedl\u00e4nder adopted Magda so that she had his last name.<ref> Magda Goebbels, Gef\u00e4hrtin des B\u00f6sen In: Der Spiegel Vol. 39, 24. September 2001 [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-20184307.html]</ref> \nOnly by 2016 it was revealed from Friedlander's residence card, In: the Berlin archives, that he was actually Magda's biological father, of  previous acquaintance with her mother, <ref> \"Der Bild\" august 19th 2016 </ref>, hence the adoption proceeding may have been required only for the parents delayed marriage. Magda, however, was educated mainly at the Belgian Order of the [[Ursulines]] of [[Virgo Fidelis Convent Senior School|Virgo Fidelis]], cared for however, by Ritschel, the mother divorcee.<ref> Magda Goebbels, Gef\u00e4hrtin des B\u00f6sen In: Der Spiegel Vol. 39, 24. September 2001 [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-20184307.html]</ref>\n\nIn 1920, while returning to school on a train, Magda met [[G\u00fcnther Quandt]], a rich German industrialist twice her age, who courted her.{{sfn|Longerich|2015|p=152}} He demanded that she change her surname back to Ritschel (having borne the name of her mother and stepfather, Friedl\u00e4nder, for many years) while converting from Ritschel's nominal [[Catholicism]] to [[Protestantism]].{{sfn|Meissner|1980|p=31}} She and Quandt were married on 4 January 1921, and her first child, [[Harald Quandt|Harald]], was born on 1 November 1921.{{sfn|Thacker|2010|p=149}} The couple divorced in 1929. In December 1931, Magda married the Berlin [[Nazi Party]] ''[[Gauleiter]]'' (and later leader of the [[Reich Ministry of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda]]) [[Joseph Goebbels]].{{sfn|Longerich|2015|pp=152, 167}}\n\nFollowing her marriage to Quandt, Magda avoided any contact with Richard Friedl\u00e4nder, was now impoverished by then, and had to earn his living with menial jobs (e.g. as a waiter). On June 15, 1938, he was deported to Buchenwald concentration camp, as persecuted Jew, within the \"[[:de: Aktion_\u201eArbeitsscheu_Reich\u201c|Arbeitsscheu Reich]]\". Already injured, he had to do hard work in the quarry, which in connection with the catastrophic living conditions, led to his death. The death certificate by the camp's doctor noted his cause of death (vague and frequently used) \"heart muscle deterioration by pneumonia\".<ref>Christian Faludi: Die Juni-Aktion\u201c 1938. Eine Dokumentation zur Radikalisierung der Juden verfolgung, Frankfurt am Main/New York 2013, S.92. [https://books.google.de/books?id=Rofk6Za152EC&printsec=frontcover&dq =Christian+Faludi: +Die+%E2%80%9EJuni-Aktion%E2%80%9C+1938&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjgmMish7jfAhUHalAKHT9GDm4Q6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q= Christian%20Faludi% 3A%20Die %20%E2%80%9EJuni-Aktion%E2%80%9C%201938&f=false]</ref> His urn was delivered to his relatives in Berlin against payment of 93 [[Reichsmark]]s, and he was eventually buried in the [[Wei\u00dfensee cemetery|Weissensee Jewish Cemetery]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n===Bibliography===\n* ''Das t\u00f6dliche Schweigen der Magda Goebbels''. In: Guido Knopp: ''History. Geheimnisse des 20. Jahrhunderts.'' C. Bertelsmann, M\u00fcnchen 2002, {{ISBN|3-570-00665-4}}, S. 65 [https://books.google.de/books?id=zhgTAQAAIAAJ&q=Das+t%C3%B6dliche+Schweigen+der+Magda+Goebbels&dq=Das+t%C3%B6dliche+Schweigen+der+Magda+Goebbels&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj0yaePi7jfAhVKmbQKHRvqB7kQ6AEIKjAA]\n* {{cite book | last = Longerich | first = Peter | year = 2015 | title = Goebbels: A Biography | publisher = Random House | location = New York | isbn = 978-1400067510 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last = Meissner | first = Hans-Otto | title = Magda Goebbels: The First Lady of the Third Reich | year = 1980 | origyear = 1978 | publisher = The Dial Press | location = New York | isbn = 978-0803762121 | ref = harv }}\n* Stefanie Sch\u00fcler-Springorum: ''Masseneinweisungen in Konzentrationslager. Aktion \u201eArbeitsscheu Reich\u201c, Novemberpogrom, Aktion \u201eGewitter\u201c''. In: Wolfgang Benz, Barbara Distel (Hrsg.): ''Der Ort des Terrors. Geschichte der nationalsozialistischen Konzentrationslager.'' Band 1: ''Die Organisation des Terrors.'' C.H. Beck, M\u00fcnchen 2005, {{ISBN|3-406-52961-5}}, S. 156\u2013164.\n* {{cite book | last = Thacker | first = Toby | title = Joseph Goebbels: Life and Death | year = 2010 | origyear = 2009 | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-230-27866-0 | ref = harv}}\n* Wolfgang Aya\u00df: \"''Asoziale\u201c im Nationalsozialismus''. Klett-Cotta, Stuttgart 1995, {{ISBN|3-608-91704-7}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friedlaender, Richard}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People who died in Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Richard Friedl\u00e4nder 1936.JPG|thumb|Richard Friedl\u00e4nder (deceased 1938 at KZ Buchenwald), stepfather of Magda Goebbels]]\n'''Richard Friedl\u00e4nder''' (born February 15, 1881 in Berlin, - February 18, 1939 [[Buchenwald concentration camp]] <ref>Totenbuch KZ Buchenwald [http://totenbuch.buchenwald.de/names/details/person/964/ref/recherche]</ref>) was a German Jewish merchant, stepfather of [[Magda Goebbels]], prisoner in the Buchenwald concentration camp and victim of the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]].\n\n== Life ==\n\nFriedl\u00e4nder was born to a wealthy Jewish Berlin merchant family. After attending junior high school, he learned the profession of a merchant and later worked as an employee in [[Brussels]]. In 1908 he married Auguste Behrend, who had divorced her first husband Oskar Ritschel, and who brought her only child Magda into the marriage.{{sfn|Meissner|1980|p=16}} Friedl\u00e4nder adopted Magda so that she had his last name.<ref> Magda Goebbels, Gef\u00e4hrtin des B\u00f6sen In: Der Spiegel Vol. 39, 24. September 2001 [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-20184307.html]</ref> \nOnly by 2016 it was revealed from Friedlander's residence card, In: the Berlin archives, that he was actually Magda's biological father, of  previous acquaintance with her mother, <ref> \"Der Bild\" august 19th 2016 </ref>, hence the adoption proceeding may have been required only for the parents delayed marriage. Magda, however, was educated mainly at the Belgian Order of the [[Ursulines]] of [[Virgo Fidelis Convent Senior School|Virgo Fidelis]], cared for however, by Ritschel, the mother divorcee.<ref> Magda Goebbels, Gef\u00e4hrtin des B\u00f6sen In: Der Spiegel Vol. 39, 24. September 2001 [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-20184307.html]</ref>\n\nIn 1920, while returning to school on a train, Magda met [[G\u00fcnther Quandt]], a rich German industrialist twice her age, who courted her.{{sfn|Longerich|2015|p=152}} He demanded that she change her surname back to Ritschel (having borne the name of her mother and stepfather, Friedl\u00e4nder, for many years) while converting from Ritschel's nominal [[Catholicism]] to [[Protestantism]].{{sfn|Meissner|1980|p=31}} She and Quandt were married on 4 January 1921, and her first child, [[Harald Quandt|Harald]], was born on 1 November 1921.{{sfn|Thacker|2010|p=149}} The couple divorced in 1929. In December 1931, Magda married the Berlin [[Nazi Party]] ''[[Gauleiter]]'' (and later leader of the [[Reich Ministry of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda]]) [[Joseph Goebbels]].{{sfn|Longerich|2015|pp=152, 167}}\n\nFollowing her marriage to Quandt, Magda avoided any contact with Richard Friedl\u00e4nder, was now impoverished by then, and had to earn his living with menial jobs (e.g. as a waiter). On June 15, 1938, he was deported to Buchenwald concentration camp, as persecuted Jew, within the \"[[:de: Aktion_\u201eArbeitsscheu_Reich\u201c|Arbeitsscheu Reich]]\". Already injured, he had to do hard work in the quarry, which in connection with the catastrophic living conditions, led to his death. The death certificate by the camp's doctor noted his cause of death (vague and frequently used) \"heart muscle deterioration by pneumonia\".<ref>Christian Faludi: Die Juni-Aktion\u201c 1938. Eine Dokumentation zur Radikalisierung der Juden verfolgung, Frankfurt am Main/New York 2013, S.92. [https://books.google.de/books?id=Rofk6Za152EC&printsec=frontcover&dq =Christian+Faludi: +Die+%E2%80%9EJuni-Aktion%E2%80%9C+1938&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjgmMish7jfAhUHalAKHT9GDm4Q6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q= Christian%20Faludi% 3A%20Die %20%E2%80%9EJuni-Aktion%E2%80%9C%201938&f=false]</ref> His urn was delivered to his relatives in Berlin against payment of 93 [[Reichsmark]]s, and he was eventually buried in the [[Wei\u00dfensee cemetery|Weissensee Jewish Cemetery]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n===Bibliography===\n* ''Das t\u00f6dliche Schweigen der Magda Goebbels''. In: Guido Knopp: ''History. Geheimnisse des 20. Jahrhunderts.'' C. Bertelsmann, M\u00fcnchen 2002, {{ISBN|3-570-00665-4}}, S. 65 [https://books.google.de/books?id=zhgTAQAAIAAJ&q=Das+t%C3%B6dliche+Schweigen+der+Magda+Goebbels&dq=Das+t%C3%B6dliche+Schweigen+der+Magda+Goebbels&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj0yaePi7jfAhVKmbQKHRvqB7kQ6AEIKjAA]\n* {{cite book | last = Longerich | first = Peter | year = 2015 | title = Goebbels: A Biography | publisher = Random House | location = New York | isbn = 978-1400067510 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last = Meissner | first = Hans-Otto | title = Magda Goebbels: The First Lady of the Third Reich | year = 1980 | origyear = 1978 | publisher = The Dial Press | location = New York | isbn = 978-0803762121 | ref = harv }}\n* Stefanie Sch\u00fcler-Springorum: ''Masseneinweisungen in Konzentrationslager. Aktion \u201eArbeitsscheu Reich\u201c, Novemberpogrom, Aktion \u201eGewitter\u201c''. In: Wolfgang Benz, Barbara Distel (Hrsg.): ''Der Ort des Terrors. Geschichte der nationalsozialistischen Konzentrationslager.'' Band 1: ''Die Organisation des Terrors.'' C.H. Beck, M\u00fcnchen 2005, {{ISBN|3-406-52961-5}}, S. 156\u2013164.\n* {{cite book | last = Thacker | first = Toby | title = Joseph Goebbels: Life and Death | year = 2010 | origyear = 2009 | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-230-27866-0 | ref = harv}}\n* Wolfgang Aya\u00df: \"''Asoziale\u201c im Nationalsozialismus''. Klett-Cotta, Stuttgart 1995, {{ISBN|3-608-91704-7}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friedlaender, Richard}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People who died in Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]]\n", "name_user": "D. H. S. Amit", "label": "safe", "comment": "/* just minor edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Friedl%C3%A4nder"}
